{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474823"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12421"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12421"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.05,0.01,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64312"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"148"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27065"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-year-old boy presents with his mother to his GP with a 5-day history of fever and rash. On examination, he has bilateral conjunctival injection, an erythematous tongue, unilateral cervical lymphadenopathy, and an erythematous polymorphous, blanching rash covering the trunk and extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation to assess for potential complications of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","CRP and ESR","Chest X-ray","FBC and CHEM-20","ECG"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is showing clear features of Kawasaki disease. He fulfils the clinical diagnostic criteria. He has a history of fever for five days along with four specific symptoms (conjunctival injection, erythematous tongue, unilateral cervical lymphadenopathy, and erythematous polymorphous rash). Kawasaki disease is an acute necrotising vasculitis with an unknown aetiology. The diagnostic criteria consist of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECOMPLETE CRITERIA\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt least five days of fever in addition to:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt least four specific symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELess than four specific symptoms and involvement of coronary arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecific symptoms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConjunctival injection (painless, bilateral, perilimbic sparing)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythematous polymorphous rash\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral changes: strawberry tongue, cracked and bleeding lips which are erythematous and dry\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChanges of upper and lower extremities: painful oedema and erythematous hands and feet\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECervical lymphadenopathy: commonly unilateral, tender, at least \u0026gt;1.5cm in diameter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINCOMPLETE CRITERIA\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis should be considered in those with a suggestive clinical presentation but insufficient symptoms to meet the criteria. Diagnosis requires abnormal investigations in these scenarios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important investigation to assess for complications of this condition. As Kawasaki\u0027s disease is a medium vessel vasculitis, it also affects the coronary arteries, which may result in coronary artery abnormalities such as aneurysms that may rupture or result in thrombosis. The echocardiogram best assesses for these cardiac complications. However, it should not delay treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECRP and ESR\u003C/strong\u003E is a laboratory test that may support the diagnosis of Kawasaki disease but is not diagnostic. Additionally, it would not be used to detect cardiac complications. Increased CRP and ESR is a non-specific finding seen in Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the assessment of Kawasaki disease complications. It may show signs of heart failure if present but does not directly assess coronary artery involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EFBC\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECHEM-20\u003C/strong\u003E can be done for patients who have insufficient symptoms to support the complete clinical diagnostic criteria. Normochromic anaemia and leucocytosis is a non-specific finding seen in Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E may show signs of myocarditis or ventricular dysfunction but is less able to pick up coronary artery abnormalities, which is the main cardiac complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delay or lack of appropriate treatment for Kawasaki disease leads to coronary artery aneurysms in 25% of cases.","Kawasaki disease is diagnosed by fever persisting for 5 days, plus at least 4 specific symptoms."],"references":["McCrindle BW, Rowley AH, Newburger JW, Burns JC, Bolger AF, Gewitz M, Baker AL, Jackson MA, Takahashi M, Shah PB, Kobayashi T, Wu MH, Saji TT, Pahl E; American Heart Association Rheumatic Fever, Endocarditis, and Kawasaki Disease Committee of the Council on Cardiovascular Disease in the Young; Council on Cardiovascular and Stroke Nursing; Council on Cardiovascular Surgery and Anesthesia; and Council on Epidemiology and Prevention. Diagnosis, Treatment, and Long-Term Management of Kawasaki Disease: A Scientific Statement for Health Professionals From the American Heart Association. Circulation. 2017 Apr 25;135(17):e927-e999. doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000484. Epub 2017 Mar 29. Erratum in: Circulation. 2019 Jul 30;140(5):e181-e184. doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000703. PMID: 28356445. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28356445/","Royal Melbourne Children\u0027s Hospital. Clinical Guidelines - Kawasaki disease.\u0022 RCH. [Internet]. Accessed 13 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Kawasaki_disease/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64312"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12421"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64312"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T12:25:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T12:26:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4929"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","